 of family has changed over the decades and there are now different types of families that have their own unique attributes and needs. Families may have one parent or two, who may or may not be of different genders. This cutting-edge book constructs a multidisciplinary perspective on family tourism by discussing various types of families; how parents and children influence travel behaviours now and in the future and how family holidays may also be linked to stress. Family Tourism: Multidisciplinary Perspectives provides a compilation of issues from academic writers around the globe, to provide a range of perspectives linked by a common theme of family tourism with a futures perspective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFamiliesxTravel. 0aFamily recreation. 0aTourism. 4aTourism industry. 4aTravel with children / family holidays. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Hospitality, Travel & Tourism.2bisacsh  aVFR travel.  afamily holidays.  afamily leisure.  afamily lifecycle.  afamily tourism experience.  afamily tourism research.  afamily tourism.  afamily travel.  afamily vacations.  asocial tourism.  asocial trends.  atravel behaviours.  atravelling with children.1 aBacker, Elisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBacker, Elisa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHughes, Howard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLord, Damian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcMahon-Beattie, Una, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMinnaert, Lynn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParker-Hodds, Luke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchänzel, Heike, econtributor.4ctb4h